  "prompt": "How long can a milkshake last out of the fridge?",
  "response": "A milkshake should not be left out at room temperature for more than **two hours**. This guideline is based on food safety standards to prevent the growth of harmful bacteria that can cause foodborne illnesses. Here are some key points to consider:\n\n1. **Time and Temperature:** \n   - **Room Temperature (below 90\u00b0F or 32\u00b0C):** Milkshakes can safely remain out for up to **two hours**.\n   - **Hot Environments (above 90\u00b0F or 32\u00b0C):** The safe duration decreases to **one hour**.\n\n2. **Ingredients Matter:** \n   - Milkshakes typically contain dairy products like milk and ice cream, which are highly perishable. Bacteria can multiply rapidly in these ingredients when left unrefrigerated.\n\n3. **Signs of Spoilage:**\n   - **Changes in Texture or Smell:** If the milkshake develops an off odor, becomes overly thick, or separates significantly, it's best to discard it.\n   - **Elapsed Time:** Even if the milkshake appears fine, adhering to the recommended time limits is crucial for safety.\n\n4. **Best Practices:**\n   - **Refrigeration:** Always store milkshakes in the refrigerator if they are not being consumed immediately.\n   - **Transporting:** If you're taking a milkshake on the go, use an insulated container with ice packs to keep it cold.\n\n5. **Health Considerations:**\n   - Consuming a milkshake that has been left out too long can increase the risk of foodborne illnesses, especially for vulnerable groups like children, the elderly, pregnant women, and individuals with weakened immune systems.\n\n**Summary:** To ensure safety and maintain quality, keep milkshakes refrigerated and avoid leaving them out at room temperature for more than two hours (or one hour in hotter conditions).",
